Mar 13 2007 	Not a great value	We stayed at the Sheraton to visit Coco Key for a quick family get away. We stayed the night of March 10th, just a Saturday nothing special. The hotel was at capacity. There were no seats in the waterpark, no lockers and no where to put your things. The kiddie area was jammed with everyone toddlers, teens and adults ..the toddler area is also the swim in theater area....not that you could hear a movie if you wanted to. The food areas and garbage cans were disgusting, there were people eating pizza in the kiddie pool. There were adults drinking beer while sitting in the kiddie pool, why aren't they in the bar? The pool was closed when a toddler with no &quot;swimmy diaper&quot; on and fouled the pool. They had to close it for 1 hour. They were not quick to clear the pool either, I did not like this. The Starbucks ran out of cream. Granted this is on their website but they had no roll aways or port a cribs but gave me a King Room and 4 wristbands for the water park, where were the other 2 people sleeping? I was not very impressed, I read the other review from Presidents day with a grain of salt thinking it was a BUSY weekend, but it was that way on a normal weekend. They came outside our room to check locks at 9pm Saturday night, thought that was strange. The elevators down had a 6-14 minute wait depending on the time of day. Quick hint...use the service elevator by vending machines to get down from the floors quickly. I was not very impressed, we have stayed in other water park/resorts. I know they are new and hope they get their act together. I would not bother going back any time soon.	
Feb 19 2007 	Staff needs some work on serving families	We stayed here over President's Day weekend, which might explain some of what happened. The hotel was at capacity, which led to long waits at the elevators and lots of cranky guests. The staff was overwhelmed, which surprised me - this place has never sold out before? Ever? I wonder if the fancy-schmantzy Arlington Millions crowd gets told that there are no extra blankets left.The kids LOVED the water park, the parents all looked annoyed because there were only enough chairs for about a quarter of the families there. The locker situation is also bad, so expect to spend time standing next to bags of your stuff while the kids are on the slides.The Starbucks in the lobby was sold out of everything but bran muffins by 7:30 am on Sunday morning. I guess it never occurred to them that families with kids might like to have breakfast in the room while the kids watch TV, but that kids don't really like bran muffins. The water park didn't open until 10:00 am, so everyone was milling around the lobby, getting impatient, for at least an hour. If I were the hotel manager, I'd open the arcade and rake in some bucks right quick from frustrated parents, but the arcade doesn't open until 10:00, either. And then, at 11:15 am, Pizza Hut was sold out of medium pizzas! 11:15 am! So much for planning for the weekend lunch rush. I couldn't decide if that was hilarious or just a pathetic ploy to get extra money out of me.So my advice is this: don't go on a holiday weekend, bring a cooler with your own breakfast supplies, expect to wait around a lot, and suck it up for the sake of the kids. The kids are going to have a great time.	
Feb 13 2007 	Great Water Park Addition	Very nice property. The water park was a very nice addition. It is perfect for kids 4-14. My family was just a bit young (6, 4, and 1) to fully enjoy the water park. We traveled mid-week - the water park was empty. I would recommend the hotel as a place to get away from a Chicago winter day.	
Jan 1 2007 	Renewed faith in customer service! CoCo Keys Rules!	My family went to visit for the grand opening of CoCo Keys Water Resort. My son is 8 and my daughter is 7. Not only did the kids LOVE the water park, so did the big people! With tube slides, body slides (for young and old), lazy river, water polo, water challenges, swim-in movie theater and AMAZING hot tub! The place was just amazing. The staff at the hotel and at the waterpark worked very hard to ensure that our trip was huge fun. I would recommend this hotel and water park to any Chicago family looking to escape the winter yicks. The fake blue sky is close enough on any gray day!	
Dec 16 2006	A Hotel Turned Home	Last summer, our house burt down and we were forced to live in a hotel while they rebuilt our house. We chose the Shearton Chicago Northwest because we knew it was by far the nicest hotel in Arlington Heights. The hotel staff was so nice and accomidating, and the hotel really did feel like home. We had two rooms connecting and they were big enough to live out of. It was nice to have tennis courts and basketball courts on the property because I play tennis and we have a basketball player in the family. GREAT STAFF, BIG ROOMS, GOOD RESTAURANTS, HOMEY FEEL. WATERPARK UNDER CONSTRUCTION NOW!!	
Oct 5 2006 	Far Far Away	This is really a nice hotel but I made a mistake in booking my stay here. I booked through Hotwire(which I love!) but I didn't know enough about the distance this hotel was from Chicago. Of course this isn't a problem if you intend to drive but I dislike driving when on vacation. If you don't drive, then be prepared to take the hotel shuttle(free) to the metro and take it into Chicago. A little inconvenient especially if you return a little late. :-) I have nothing but positive comments about the hotel, I chose it mainly because of the low price and this is totally my fault, but just be forewarned about the distance.	
Sep 3 2006 	Great Home Base For Exploring Chicagoland!	Hotwire led me to the Sheraton Chicago Northwest in Arlington Heights for a 3 night stay from 8/20-8/23/06. I paid $52/night for two large rooms (#817 &amp; #925). The hotel is just off the Euclid Ave. exit of IL 53 &amp; is also near the Woodfield shopping area, I-90, &amp; I-290.I had read the previous reviews on TA after I booked my stay at the Sheraton, so I was aware of what was going on. (That may have explained my low Hotwire rate.) At the time I stayed, the parking lot (but not the hotel entrance itself) was a little cluttered with construction activity for both the new waterpark &amp; some renovation activity taking place on the hotel itself. The hotel placed a placard in each room explaining what was going on, to its credit. I did not have any problems with construction noise during my time at the Sheraton, &amp; there was still ample parking to be had throughout my stay.Although I had not requested a room with two double beds in advance of my arrival, the staff was able to accomodate my request without any problem.My room had two large double beds with probably the most comfortable pillows I have ever seen. The climate control was very effective, with the thermostat allowing temperature control down to 0.5 degree. In general, no problems whatsoever. My only wish would be for a mini-fridge in the room.The hotel is located only about 5 minutes from a commuter station (Metra Rail, Arlington Park) which is great for trips into the city. If you are a Chicago Cubs or Bears fan, there is direct Pace bus service leaving from nearby Schaumburg to Wrigley Field &amp; Soldier Field. You will probably need a car to explore the immediate area, but the hotel provides shuttle service to O'Hare &amp; Enterprise rental cars are available at the front desk.So, all in all, a pleasant experience with this Sheraton.	
Jun 29 2006	Decent stay near airport. Waterpark coming 2006	Waterpark explains contruction comment in last post. I stay in this hotel once a year for a convention, and although rates didn't go up during contruction, they are expected to go up after it opens. The rooms are large (enough to sleep 2 extras on daybeds), have always been clean, have comfy beds and it's quiet. Their meeting rooms are sprawled, and it can be quite a walk. I also think their older main areas look a bit worn. I've found it to be safe, and the hotel staff to be very understanding during a crowded event. Overall, I recommned this hotel for meetings and conventions, and to individuals, but only if you get a good rate. One issue: We spilled some red drink mixer in the bathroom, used hotel towels to clean it up, and they charged us for the towels, since they said it wouldn't come clean, even though they washed it twice. For what they charged us, would have liked to at least keep the towels.	
